<article title='Bipyramid'><paragraph><template><target>For</target><arg>Dipyramid</arg><arg>mountain</arg><arg>Dipyramid (Alaska)</arg></template><template><target>more footnotes</target><arg name="date">March 2013</arg></template></paragraph><table class="wikitable" bgcolor="#ffffff" cellpadding="5" align="right" style="margin-left:10px" width="280"><tablerow><tablehead bgcolor="#e7dcc3" colspan="2">Set of regular right bipyramids</tablehead></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell align="center" colspan="2"><link><target>File:Hexagonale bipiramide.png</target><part>200px</part><part>hexagonal bipyramid</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br>(Example hexagonal form)</tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell bgcolor="#e7dcc3">Coxeter diagram</tablecell><tablecell><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>n</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell bgcolor="#e7dcc3"><link><target>Schlfli symbol</target></link></tablecell><tablecell>{ } + {n}</tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell bgcolor="#e7dcc3">Faces</tablecell><tablecell>2<italics>n</italics><space/><link><target>triangle</target><trail>s</trail></link></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell bgcolor="#e7dcc3">Edges</tablecell><tablecell>3<italics>n</italics></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell bgcolor="#e7dcc3">Vertices</tablecell><tablecell>2 +<space/><italics>n</italics></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell bgcolor="#e7dcc3"><link><target>Face configuration</target></link></tablecell><tablecell>V4.4.<italics>n</italics></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell bgcolor="#e7dcc3"><link><target>List of spherical symmetry groups</target><part>Symmetry group</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Dihedral symmetry in three dimensions</target><part>D<xhtml:sub><italics>n</italics>h</xhtml:sub></part></link>, [<italics>n</italics>,2], (*<italics>n</italics>22), order 4<italics>n</italics></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell bgcolor="#e7dcc3"><link><target>Point groups in three dimensions#Rotation groups</target><part>Rotation group</part></link></tablecell><tablecell>D<xhtml:sub><italics>n</italics></xhtml:sub>, [<italics>n</italics>,2]<xhtml:sup>+</xhtml:sup>, (<italics>n</italics>22), order 2<italics>n</italics></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell bgcolor="#e7dcc3"><link><target>Dual polyhedron</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Prism (geometry)</target><part>''n''-gonal prism</part></link></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell bgcolor="#e7dcc3">Properties</tablecell><tablecell>convex,<space/><link><target>face-transitive</target></link></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell bgcolor="#e7dcc3"><link><target>Net (polyhedron)</target><part>Net</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:Generalized bipyramid net.svg</target><part>150px</part><part>A ''n''-gonal bipyramid net, in this example a pentagonal bipyramid</part></link></tablecell></tablerow></table><paragraph><link><target>File:bipiramide5.jpg</target><part>thumb</part><part></part><part>A bipyramid made with<space/><link><target>drinking straw</target><part>straw</part><trail>s</trail></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>rubber band</target><part>elastic</part><trail>s</trail></link>. An extra axial straw is added which doesn't exist in the simple polyhedron</part></link>An<space/><italics>n</italics>-gonal<space/><bold>bipyramid</bold><space/>or<space/><bold>dipyramid</bold><space/>is a<space/><link><target>polyhedron</target></link><space/>formed by joining an<space/><italics>n</italics>-gonal<space/><link><target>Pyramid (geometry)</target><part>pyramid</part></link><space/>and its<space/><link><target>mirror image</target></link><space/>base-to-base. An<space/><italics>n</italics>-gonal bipyramid has 2<italics>n</italics><space/><link><target>triangle</target></link><space/>faces, 3<italics>n</italics><space/>edges, and 2+<italics>n</italics><space/>vertices.</paragraph><paragraph>The referenced<space/><italics>n</italics>-gon in the name of the bipyramids is not an external face but an internal one, existing on the primary symmetry plane which connects the two pyramid halves.</paragraph><heading level='2'>Right, oblique and concave bipyramids</heading><paragraph>A<space/><bold>right bipyramid</bold><space/>has two points above and below the<space/><link><target>centroid</target></link><space/>of its base. Nonright bipyramids are called<space/><bold>oblique bipyramids</bold>. A<space/><bold>regular bipyramid</bold><space/>has a<space/><link><target>regular polygon</target></link><space/>internal face and is usually implied to be a<space/><italics>right bipyramid</italics>. A right bipyramid can be represented as { }+P for internal polygon P, and a regular n<italics>-</italics>bipyramid { } + {n}.</paragraph><paragraph>A<space/><bold>concave bipyramid</bold><space/>has a concave interior polygon.</paragraph><list type='ident'><listitem><link><target>File:Concave quadrilateral bipyramid.png</target><part>160px</part></link></listitem></list><paragraph>The<space/><link><target>face-transitive</target></link><space/>regular bipyramids are the<space/><link><target>dual polyhedra</target></link><space/>of the<space/><link><target>Prism (geometry)</target><part>uniform prisms</part></link><space/>and will generally have<space/><link><target>isosceles triangle</target></link><space/>faces.</paragraph><paragraph>A bipyramid can be<space/><link><target>Perspective projection</target><part>projected</part></link><space/>on a sphere or<space/><link><target>globe</target></link><space/>as<space/><italics>n</italics><space/>equally spaced lines of<space/><link><target>longitude</target></link><space/>going from<space/><link><target>Geographical pole</target><part>pole</part></link><space/>to pole, and<space/><link><target>Bisection</target><part>bisected</part></link><space/>by a line around the<space/><link><target>equator</target></link>.</paragraph><paragraph>Bipyramid<space/><link><target>face (geometry)</target><part>face</part><trail>s</trail></link>, projected as<space/><link><target>spherical triangle</target><trail>s</trail></link>, represent the fundamental domains in the<space/><link><target>List of spherical symmetry groups#Dihedral</target><part>dihedral symmetry</part></link><space/>D<xhtml:sub>nh</xhtml:sub>.</paragraph><heading level='2'>Volume</heading><paragraph>The<space/><link><target>volume</target></link><space/>of a bipyramid is<space/><extension extension_name='math'>\scriptstyle{V =} \tfrac{2}{3} \scriptstyle{Bh}</extension><space/>where<space/><italics>B</italics><space/>is the area of the base and<space/><italics>h</italics><space/>the height from the base to the apex. This works for any location of the apex, provided that<space/><italics>h</italics><space/>is measured as the<space/><link><target>perpendicular</target></link><space/>distance from the<space/><link><target>plane (geometry)</target><part>plane</part></link><space/>which contains the base.</paragraph><paragraph>The volume of a bipyramid whose base is a regular<space/><italics>n</italics>-sided<space/><link><target>polygon</target></link><space/>with side length<space/><italics>s</italics><space/>and whose height is<space/><italics>h</italics><space/>is therefore:</paragraph><list type='ident'><listitem><extension extension_name='math'>V = \frac{n}{6}hs^2 \cot\frac{\pi}{n}.</extension></listitem></list><heading level='2'>Equilateral triangle bipyramids</heading><paragraph>Only three kinds of bipyramids can have all edges of the same length (which implies that all faces are<space/><link><target>equilateral triangle</target><trail>s</trail></link>, and thus the bipyramid is a<space/><link><target>deltahedron</target></link>): the<space/><link><target>Triangular dipyramid</target><part>triangular</part></link>, tetragonal, and<space/><link><target>Pentagonal dipyramid</target><part>pentagonal</part></link><space/>bipyramids. The tetragonal bipyramid with identical edges, or<space/><link><target>regular octahedron</target></link>, counts among the<space/><link><target>Platonic solid</target><trail>s</trail></link>, while the triangular and pentagonal bipyramids with identical edges count among the<space/><link><target>Johnson solid</target><trail>s</trail></link><space/>(J12 and J13).</paragraph><table class="wikitable"><tablerow align="center" valign="bottom"><tablecell><link><target>Image:Triangular dipyramid.png</target><part>100px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:octahedron.svg</target><part>100px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:Pentagonal dipyramid.png</target><part>100px</part></link></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow align="center" valign="top"><tablecell><link><target>Triangular bipyramid</target></link></tablecell><tablecell>Square bipyramid<xhtml:br></xhtml:br>(<link><target>Octahedron</target></link>)</tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Pentagonal bipyramid</target></link></tablecell></tablerow></table><heading level='2'>Kalidescopic symmetry</heading><paragraph>If the base is regular and the line through the<space/><link><target>Apex (geometry)</target><part>apexes</part></link><space/>intersects the base at its center, the<space/><link><target>List of spherical symmetry groups</target><part>symmetry group</part></link><space/>of the<space/><italics>n</italics>-agonal bipyramid has<space/><link><target>Dihedral symmetry in three dimensions</target><part>dihedral symmetry</part></link><space/>D<xhtml:sub><italics>n</italics>h</xhtml:sub><space/>of order 4<italics>n</italics>, except in the case of a regular octahedron, which has the larger<space/><link><target>octahedral symmetry</target></link><space/>group O<xhtml:sub>h</xhtml:sub><space/>of order 48, which has three versions of D<xhtml:sub>4h</xhtml:sub><space/>as subgroups. The<space/><link><target>Point groups in three dimensions#Rotation groups</target><part>rotation group</part></link><space/>is D<xhtml:sub><italics>n</italics></xhtml:sub><space/>of order 2<italics>n</italics>, except in the case of a regular octahedron, which has the larger symmetry group O of order 24, which has three versions of D<xhtml:sub>4</xhtml:sub><space/>as subgroups.</paragraph><paragraph>The digonal faces of a<space/><link><target>Spherical polyhedron</target><part>spherical</part></link><space/><italics>2n</italics>-bipyramid represents the fundamental domains of<space/><link><target>dihedral symmetry in three dimensions</target></link>: D<xhtml:sub>nh</xhtml:sub>, [n,2], (*n22), order<space/><italics>4n</italics>. The reflection domains can be shown as alternately colored triangles as mirror images.</paragraph><table class="wikitable"><tablerow><tablehead>D<xhtml:sub>1h</xhtml:sub></tablehead><tablehead>D<xhtml:sub>2h</xhtml:sub></tablehead><tablehead>D<xhtml:sub>3h</xhtml:sub></tablehead><tablehead>D<xhtml:sub>4h</xhtml:sub></tablehead><tablehead>D<xhtml:sub>5h</xhtml:sub></tablehead><tablehead>D<xhtml:sub>6h</xhtml:sub></tablehead><tablehead>...</tablehead></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell><link><target>Image:Spherical digonal bipyramid2.png</target><part>120px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:Spherical square bipyramid2.png</target><part>120px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:Spherical hexagonal bipyramid2.png</target><part>120px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:Spherical octagonal bipyramid2.png</target><part>120px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:Spherical decagonal bipyramid2.png</target><part>120px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:Spherical dodecagonal bipyramid2.png</target><part>120px</part></link></tablecell></tablerow></table><heading level='2'>Right regular bipyramids</heading><paragraph><template><target>Bipyramids</target></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>Scalenohedron</heading><paragraph>A<space/><bold>scalenohedron</bold><space/>is topologically identical to a 2<italics>n</italics>-bipyramid, but contains congruent<space/><link><target>scalene triangle</target><trail>s</trail></link>.<space/></paragraph><paragraph>There are two types. In one type the 2<italics>n</italics><space/>vertices around the center alternate in rings above and below the center. In the other type, the 2<italics>n</italics><space/>vertices are on the same plane, but alternate in two radii.</paragraph><paragraph>The first has 2-fold rotation axes mid-edge around the sides, reflection planes through the vertices, and n-fold rotation symmetry on its axis, representing symmetry D<xhtml:sub><italics>n</italics>d</xhtml:sub>, [2<xhtml:sup>+</xhtml:sup>,2<italics>n</italics>], (2*n) , order 2<italics>n</italics>. In<space/><link><target>crystallography</target></link>, 8-sided and 12-sided scalenohedra exist.<extension extension_name='ref'>http://www.tulane.edu/~sanelson/eens211/forms_zones_habit.htm</extension><space/>All of these forms are<space/><link><target>isohedron</target><trail>s</trail></link>.</paragraph><paragraph>The second has symmetry D<xhtml:sub><italics>n</italics></xhtml:sub>, [2,<italics>n</italics>], (*nn2), order 2<italics>n</italics>.</paragraph><paragraph>The smallest scalenohedron has 8 faces and is topologically identical to the regular octahedron. The second type is a<space/><italics>rhombic bipyramid</italics>. The first type has 6 vertices can be represented as (0,0,1), (1,0,<italics>z</italics>), (0,1,-<italics>z</italics>), where<space/><italics>z</italics><space/>is a parameter between 0 and 1, creating a regular octahedron at<space/><italics>z</italics>=0.0, and becomes a<space/><link><target>disphenoid</target></link><space/>with merged coplanar faces at<space/><italics>z</italics>=1.0. Beyond 1, it becomes concave.</paragraph><table class="wikitable"><tablecaption>4-scalenohedron geometric variations</tablecaption><tablerow><tablehead>z=0.10</tablehead><tablehead>z=0.25</tablehead><tablehead>z=0.50</tablehead><tablehead>z=0.95</tablehead><tablehead>z=1.5</tablehead></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell><link><target>File:4-scalenohedron-01.png</target><part>160px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>File:4-scalenohedron-025.png</target><part>160px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>File:4-scalenohedron-05.png</target><part>160px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>File:4-scalenohedron-095.png</target><part>160px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>File:4-scalenohedron-15.png</target><part>160px</part></link></tablecell></tablerow></table><heading level='2'>Star bipyramids</heading><paragraph>Self-intersecting bipyramids exist with a<space/><link><target>star polygon</target></link><space/>central figure, defined by triangular faces connecting each polygon edge to these two points. A {p/q} bipyramid has<space/><link><target>Coxeter diagram</target></link><space/><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>p</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>q</arg><arg>node</arg></template>.</paragraph><table class="wikitable"><tablerow align="center"><tablehead><link><target>Pentagrammic bipyramid</target><part>5/2</part></link></tablehead><tablehead>7/2</tablehead><tablehead>7/3</tablehead><tablehead>8/3</tablehead><tablehead>9/2</tablehead><tablehead>9/4</tablehead><tablehead>10/3</tablehead><tablehead>11/2</tablehead><tablehead>11/3</tablehead><tablehead>11/4</tablehead><tablehead>11/5</tablehead><tablehead>12/5</tablehead></tablerow><tablerow align="center" valign="top"><tablecell><link><target>Image:Pentagram Dipyramid.png</target><part>50px</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>5</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:7-2 dipyramid.png</target><part>60px</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>7</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:7-3 dipyramid.png</target><part>60px</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>7</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>3x</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:8-3 dipyramid.png</target><part>60px</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>8</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>3x</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:9-2 dipyramid.png</target><part>60px</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>9</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:9-4 dipyramid.png</target><part>60px</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>9</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>4</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:10-3 dipyramid.png</target><part>60px</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>10</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>3x</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:11-2 dipyramid.png</target><part>60px</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>11</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:11-3 dipyramid.png</target><part>60px</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>11</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>3x</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:11-4 dipyramid.png</target><part>60px</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>11</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>4</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:11-5 dipyramid.png</target><part>60px</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>11</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>5</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>Image:12-5 dipyramid.png</target><part>60px</part></link><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><template><target>CDD</target><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>2x</arg><arg>node_f1</arg><arg>12</arg><arg>rat</arg><arg>5</arg><arg>node</arg></template></tablecell></tablerow></table><paragraph><link><target>isohedron</target><part>isohedral</part></link><space/>even-sided stars can also be made with<space/><link><target>regular skew polygon</target><part>zig-zag offplane</part></link><space/>vertices, in-out<space/><link><target>isotoxal polygon</target><part>isotoxal</part></link><space/>forms, or both, like this {8/3} form:</paragraph><table class="wikitable"><tablerow><tablehead>Regular</tablehead><tablehead>Zig-zag regular</tablehead><tablehead>Isotoxal</tablehead><tablehead>Zig-zag isotoxal</tablehead></tablerow><tablerow><tablecell><link><target>File:8-3 dipyramid.png</target><part>150px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>File:8-3-bipyramid zigzag.png</target><part>150px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>File:8-3-bipyramid-inout.png</target><part>150px</part></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>File:8-3-dipyramid zigzag inout.png</target><part>150px</part></link></tablecell></tablerow></table><heading level='2'>4-polytopes with bipyramid cells</heading><paragraph>The<space/><link><target>Dual polyhedron#Dual polytopes and tessellations</target><part>dual</part></link><space/>of the<space/><link><target>Rectification (geometry)</target><part>rectification</part></link><space/>of each<space/><link><target>convex regular 4-polytope</target><trail>s</trail></link><space/>is a<space/><link><target>cell-transitive</target></link><space/><link><target>4-polytope</target></link><space/>with bipyramidal cells. In the following, the apex vertex of the bipyramid is A and an equator vertex is E. The distance between adjacent vertices on the equator EE=1, the apex to equator edge is AE and the distance between the apices is AA. The bipyramid 4-polytope will have V<xhtml:sub>A</xhtml:sub><space/>vertices where the apices of N<xhtml:sub>A</xhtml:sub><space/>bipyramids meet. It will have V<xhtml:sub>E</xhtml:sub><space/>vertices where the type E vertices of N<xhtml:sub>E</xhtml:sub><space/>bipyramids meet. N<xhtml:sub>AE</xhtml:sub><space/>bipyramids meet along each type AE edge. N<xhtml:sub>EE</xhtml:sub><space/>bipyramids meet along each type EE edge. C<xhtml:sub>AE</xhtml:sub><space/>is the cosine of the dihedral angle along an AE edge. C<xhtml:sub>EE</xhtml:sub><space/>is the cosine of the<space/><link><target>dihedral angle</target></link><space/>along an EE edge. As cells must fit around an edge,N<xhtml:sub>AA</xhtml:sub><space/>cos<xhtml:sup>1</xhtml:sup>(C<xhtml:sub>AA</xhtml:sub>) 2&amp;pi;, N<xhtml:sub>AE</xhtml:sub><space/>cos<xhtml:sup>1</xhtml:sup>(C<xhtml:sub>AE</xhtml:sub>) 2&amp;pi;.</paragraph><table class="wikitable"><tablerow><tablehead colspan="9">4-polytope Properties</tablehead><tablehead colspan="6">Bipyramid Properties</tablehead></tablerow><tablerow align="center"><tablehead>Dual of</tablehead><tablehead><link><target>Coxeter-Dynkin diagram</target><part>Coxeter<xhtml:br></xhtml:br>diagram</part></link></tablehead><tablehead>Cells</tablehead><tablehead>V<xhtml:sub>A</xhtml:sub></tablehead><tablehead>V<xhtml:sub>E</xhtml:sub></tablehead><tablehead>N<xhtml:sub>A</xhtml:sub></tablehead><tablehead>N<xhtml:sub>E</xhtml:sub></tablehead><tablehead>N<xhtml:sub>AE</xhtml:sub></tablehead><tablehead>N<xhtml:sub>EE</xhtml:sub></tablehead><tablehead>Cell</ta